**Implementing Input Masks and Validation for Different Types of Data**

To implement input masks and validation for different types of data in an HTML form, you can use the following techniques:

### 1. Using Input Masks

Input masks are used to restrict user input to a specific format, such as a phone number or ZIP code. You can use libraries like [Inputmask](https://github.com/RobinHerbots/Inputmask) or [Masked Input](https://github.com/digitalBush/jquery.maskedinput) to implement input masks.

```html
<input type="tel" id="phone" name="phone" required>
<script>
    $(document).ready(function() {
        $('#phone').inputmask('999-999-9999');
    });
</script>
```

### 2. Using Regular Expressions

Regular expressions can be used to validate user input and ensure it meets the required format. You can use JavaScript or a server-side programming language to implement regular expressions.

```javascript
const phoneInput = document.getElementById('phone');
phoneInput.addEventListener('input', () => {
    const phoneValue = phoneInput.value;
    if (!/^\d{3}-\d{3}-\d{4}$/.test(phoneValue)) {
        phoneInput.setCustomValidity('Invalid phone number format');
    } else {
        phoneInput.setCustomValidity('');
    }
});
```

### 3. Using HTML5 Input Types

HTML5 input types can be used to restrict user input to a specific format, such as a phone number or email address.

```html
<input type="tel" id="phone" name="phone" required>
<input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>
```

### 4. Implementing Custom Validation

Custom validation can be implemented using JavaScript or a server-side programming language to ensure user input meets the required format.

```javascript
const zipInput = document.getElementById('zip');
zipInput.addEventListener('input', () => {
    const zipValue = zipInput.value;
    if (!/^\d{5}$/.test(zipValue)) {
        zipInput.setCustomValidity('Invalid ZIP code format');
    } else {
        zipInput.setCustomValidity('');
    }
});
```

### 5. Using a Validation Library

Consider using a validation library, such as [JQuery Validation](https://jqueryvalidation.org/) or [Validator.js](https://github.com/validatorjs/validator.js), to handle input validation and formatting.

### Example Secure HTML Form

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Secure Form</title>
    <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/inputmask/4.0.9/inputmask.bundle.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
    <form action="https://example.com/submit" method="post">
        <label for="phone">Phone:</label>
        <input type="tel" id="phone" name="phone" required pattern="[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{4}">
        <br><br>
        <label for="email">Email:</label>
        <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>
        <br><br>
        <label for="zip">ZIP:</label>
        <input type="tel" id="zip" name="zip" required pattern="[0-9]{5}">
        <br><br>
        <input type="submit" value="Submit">
    </form>
    <script>
        $(document).ready(function() {
            $('#phone').inputmask('999-999-9999');
            $('#zip').inputmask('99999');
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

By following these guidelines and best practices, you can create a secure HTML form that collects different types of data securely while ensuring compliance with privacy regulations.
